<div id=3D"outline-container-1" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"1">The Flambda2 Snippets, by OCamlPro</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-1">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/blog-the-flambda2-snippets-=
by-ocamlpro/14331/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/blog-the-flambda2-snippets=
-by-ocamlpro/14331/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgef35e91" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgef35e91">OCamlPro announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgef35e91">
<p>
Greetings Cameleers,
</p>

<p>
Today, we are excited to share with you a first glance at some redactional =
work
that has been brewing behind at the scenes at OCamlPro for quite a some time
now!
</p>

<p>
We are starting a series of blogposts on the Flambda2 project. The goals are
plenty, one of them being to give all readers an idea of the inner workings=
 of
this great piece of software, 10 years of research &amp; development in the=
 making.
</p>

<p>
The first two episodes are rather special to the series:
</p>

<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li><a href=3D"https://ocamlpro.com/blog/2024_03_18_the_flambda2_snippets_0=
/">Episode 0</a> gives context and broader information on both the Flambda2=
 Optimising Compiler project, and the series of blogposts itself.</li>

<li><a href=3D"https://ocamlpro.com/blog/2024_03_19_the_flambda2_snippets_1=
/">Episode 1</a>, on the other hand, steps right into the subject at hand a=
nd covers some of the foundational design decisions of this compiler.</li>
</ul>

<p>
We await your feedback below, and hope that you will enjoy reading these po=
sts, and all ensuing
ones!
</p>

<p>
Kind regards,
The OCamlPro Team
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-2" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"2">Eio 1.0: First major release</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-2">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-eio-1-0-first-major-rel=
ease/14334/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-eio-1-0-first-major-release/1=
4334/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org91b1cee" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"org91b1cee">Sudha Parimala announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-org91b1cee">
<p>
I'm happy to announce the release of <a href=3D"https://github.com/ocaml-mu=
lticore/eio/releases/tag/v1.0">Eio
1.0</a>, its first major release. Eio
started as an experimental effects-based library by the same team that was =
working on Multicore
OCaml. We did not initially plan on upstreaming effects with OCaml 5.0. How=
ever, thanks to the
efforts from the multicore team and OCaml core developers, effect handlers =
shipped with OCaml 5.0
(making it one of the first mainstream languages to do so). This presented =
the opportunity to
develop effect-based concurrency libraries for OCaml, and Eio was the first=
 of the lot..
</p>

<p>
Find more about the journey of Eio in this post &#x2013; <a href=3D"https:/=
/tarides.com/blog/2024-03-20-eio-1-0-release-introducing-a-new-effects-base=
d-i-o-library-for-ocaml/"> Eio 1.0 Release: Introducing a new
Effects-Based I/O Library for
OCaml</a>
</p>

<p>
This is the beginning of the journey towards effect-based schedulers! We ar=
e keen to hear from you
all to shape up what would be Eio 2.0.
</p>

<p>
If you're looking to get started with Eio, the
<a href=3D"https://github.com/ocaml-multicore/eio/blob/main/README.md">READ=
ME</a> is a good place to start.
Additionally, @talex5's <a href=3D"https://watch.ocaml.org/w/1k1T919WGXoT4t=
jnRZEmMd">video introduction</a>,
and <a href=3D"https://github.com/ocaml-multicore/icfp-2023-eio-tutorial">t=
utorial to port your Lwt applications to
Eio</a> serve as good primers.
</p>

<p>
I'd like to thank all the contributors for their work and users for their t=
houghtful feedback. As
always, happy to hear feedback about Eio.
</p>

<p>
Happy hacking!
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-3" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"3">ppx_minidebug 1.3.0: toward a logging framework</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-3">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-ppx-minidebug-1-3-0-tow=
ard-a-logging-framework/14213/3">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-ppx-minide=
bug-1-3-0-toward-a-logging-framework/14213/3</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgc52e31b" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgc52e31b">Lukasz Stafiniak announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgc52e31b">
<p>
Happy to announce ppx_minidebug 1.5.0. It should soon propagate to the opam=
 repository. Two new
features since 1.4.0:
</p>
<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li><code>[%log_entry header_string; body...]</code> syntax to explicitly c=
reate log subtrees without polluting with source location information. Note=
 that if you want the source location you could always do <code>let _for_de=
bug : type... =3D body... in...</code>.</li>
<li><p>
Minimalistic flame graphs. Example:
</p>


<div id=3D"orgb8a9587" class=3D"figure">
<p><img src=3D"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/business7/uploads/ocaml/opt=
imized/2X/c/ce80302bd2abf9dbefd401cd7297184da0fa2ad6_2_1380x414.png" alt=3D=
"ce80302bd2abf9dbefd401cd7297184da0fa2ad6_2_1380x414.png" />
</p>
</div>

<p>
(Note that the output is very configurable, e.g. by default the <code>at el=
apsed</code> time information is
not printed.)
</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
